<br>
1. Shields as resist gear. Warriors forced to ghetto bash do not keep a shield equipped all the time. We swap the shield out with our offhand weapon when the Bash button recycles. The length of time the shield is actually equipped is negligible and so any resists on the shield do me no good. I'll stick with my Iksar targ shield thanks and find an offhand weapon with resists if thats what I need.<br>
<br>
2. It took me two levels of experience grinding (lvls 49 - 51) to get my bash skill from 98 to 184. But I have the advantage of a shaman partner to keep my agility and dexterity buffed constantly while grinding exp. Bash is not an easy skill to raise above 150 and any warrior who's ghetto bashed their skill that high knows it.<br>
<br>
3. Bashing doesn't move a mob around any more or less than melee attacks, so saying that the &quot;push&quot; a mob gets from a bash may interrupt a spell is irrelevant. The 5-7 attacks with my offhand weapon have just as much chance of interrupting a caster as the one bash will. Is the additional chance of a stun worth it?<br>
<br>
4. I developed my bash skill because it is a skill to be developed. I've found its more useful to try for a stun when a mob is running away than as a means of interrupting spellcasting. I'm also developing my beg skill as a means of taunting, despite the fact that I deplore it as a &quot;gimmick&quot;, because, like bash, other people I group with feel more comfortable when I do these things even though the impact of these skills on my overall effectiveness is minor. <p>Mukaz Razorscales<BR>
Champion of the 51st Legion of Cabilis<BR>
Friend of Prism<BR>
