How many warriors out there carry shields to train/use?<br>
A warrior's job is quite simple. GET AGGRO AND KEEP IT......<br>
Expecting a warrior to bash when he can't without using a shield is unfair. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Regarding your comment about a warrior's job is to get aggro and keep it.... From my experience, bashing helps me keep aggro, much in the same way a pally uses stuns to get the mob's attention.  If I'm having trouble keeping aggro, I'll bash immediately before a taunt, which seems to increase the mob's hatred towards me.<br>
<br>
Ghetto bashing is NOT a pain in the ass, however it does require a minimal amount of skill and patience.  I've done it so much, even on non-casters, that it's become second nature, even after level 55.  And training up your bash skill isn't too difficult either.  Just like anything else, it takes time and practice, but the payoff is well worth it.  Mine is maxed and stays that way for one simple reason.  I'm going to do whatever I can in my power to be the best warrior I can be in whatever situation arises.<br>
<br>
Whoever says bash is worthless has never duo'ed exp with a shammy.  Shammy casts haste on the warrior, slow on the mob, and the warrior times his bashes to land just before the mob is about to attack.  The warrior will hardly get hit, and the exp will flow in nicely.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Ever fight in Seb and have a frog run on you because either someone didn't snare in time or root broke?  Bash holds it long enough for a snare/root to be cast so the froggie doesn't get to bring back 10 of his friends for a nice group wipeout.<br>
<br>
Bash is also great for momentarily stopping a mob from beating on your cleric when they've drawn aggro.  Gives a warrior more time to regain aggro.<br>
<br>
Ever pull indoors without SOW?  Especially in places like Velks, bash is an invaluable skill to have.  Aggro a mob with an arrow, then, when it eventually catches up to you, turn around and bash it, giving you some time to get a little ahead of it.  Repeat as necessary.  Works especially well on those backstabbing little buggers.  Oh, and while you're bashing, turn on auto-attack so you hold aggro better once the mob gets into camp.<br>
<br>
Ever had to run for your life to a zone line?  Again, turn around and bash if the mob is right on your heels.  This improves your chances of survival dramatically.<br>
<br>
As for relying on kick to interrupt spells.....I seem to remember reading that kick has only a &quot;chance&quot; to stun after level 55.  I have noticed it interrupting spells, but I swear it's not all the time.  However, I believe a landed bash will always interrupt a spell on a mob for which it is possible to do so, provided that mob doesn't make a successful roll for regaining concentration.  Also, the kick skill cap is lower than bash, meaning bash will have a greater chance to land than kick.  Other warriors should correct me if I misunderstand how kick works.<br>
<br>
This is only an issue because Verant created differences within the warrior class based on race.  We don't have to like it, but playing a small race warrior means we have to live with it.  Oh, and don't forget about the advantage that ogres get about being unstunnable from a frontal attack.  Even with these 2 limitations, I enjoy playing my assling warrior and wouldn't start over as a large race if I had to.<br>
<br>
Several people summed this up perfectly.  You do what you have to do under the circumstances to get the job done regardless of who you are or what class you play.  If you consistently neglect doing something to help the group because it's a pain in the ass and you cause a TPWO or unnecessary downtime, don't expect to ever group or raid with me again.<br>
<br>
It's not my job to bash?  Phhbbbtttt....now go away, or I shall taunt you a second time. <p><P><img src=http://zencore.home.mindspring.com/kleg.gif><P><BR>
56 Myrmidon Tanklet and Officer of the Valiant Crusaders, equipped with built-in fear<BR>
